  "The cross product, particularly regarding hermitian under": "",
  "Quantum mechanics uses the Hermitian inner product where <psi|phi> = sum of conjugate(psi_i) * phi_i. This ensures <psi|psi> is real and non-negative, representing the probability normalization.": "",
  "Observable quantities in quantum mechanics are represented by which type of matrix?": "",
  "Diagonal matrices only": "",
  "Upper triangular matrices": "",
  "Hermitian (self-adjoint) matrices: A = A*": "",
  "Any invertible matrix": "",
  "Observables are Hermitian matrices (A = A*, where A* is the conjugate transpose). Hermitian matrices always have real eigenvalues, which correspond to the possible measurement outcomes.": "",
