  "i and -i": "",
  "1 and 2": "",
  "0 and 1": "",
  "det(X - lambda*I) = -lambda^2 + 1 = 0 gives lambda = +1 and -1. The Pauli-X matrix is Hermitian, so its eigenvalues are real.": "",
  "If a qubit is in state |psi> = (1/sqrt(2))|0> + (1/sqrt(2))|1>, what is the probability of measuring |0>?": "",
  "1/sqrt(2)": "",
  "1/2": "",
  "1/4": "",
  "1": "",
  "The probability of measuring |0> is |<0|psi>|^2 = |1/sqrt(2)|^2 = 1/2. This is Born's rule: the measurement probability equals the squared magnitude of the inner product with the measurement basis state.": "",
  "Quantum gates are represented by which type of matrix?": "",
  "Singular matrices": "",
  "Symmetric matrices": "",
  "Positive definite matrices": "",
  "Unitary matrices: U*U = I": "",
  "Quantum gates are unitary matrices because quantum evolution must preserve the total probability (norm) of the state vector. U*U = I ensures ||U|psi>|| = ||psi|| = 1.": "",
  "The Hadamard gate H = (1/sqrt(2))[[1, 1], [1, -1]] maps |0> to which state?": "",
